<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-12-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-12-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="185" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.512/62.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Minister <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-12-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 20, 1915</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your 807, October 29. Department reiterates its views expressed in its
                            No. 90, May 4, 1914,<note n="67" xml:id="d185fn67">
                                <ref target="frus1914#pg_122">Id. 122</ref>.</note> predicating its
                            consent to stamp tax upon assent by other foreign Governments, which
                            apparently has been refused.</p>
                        <p>Inform interested Americans, however, they may think it best to view
                            matter in practical light of probable decision Chinese courts respecting
                            unstamped documents.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>